Exploring drug exposure in the NCI-60 cell lines with PLIER

July 2019

This notebook is derived from the Alexs Lemonade Stand Foundation Childhood Cancer Data Lab training workshop materials.

Introduction to the data

In this exercise, well work with data from GEO accession GSE116436 that was processed with refine.bio.

Heres an excerpt of the description from the authors (Monks et al. Cancer Res. 2018.):

To identify patterns of drug-induced gene modulation that occur across different cell types, we measured gene expression changes across NCI-60 cell lines after exposure to 15 anticancer agents.

Weve supplied the following to you:

  • A PLIER model that was trained on the expression data from this experiment (models/NCI60_PLIER_model.RDS) (PLIER publication: Mao et al. bioRxiv. 2017.)
  • The sample metadata (data/GSE116436/metadata_GSE116436_cleaned.tsv)

Weve trained the PLIER model already in the interest of time, but more information about training a PLIER model yourself can be found here.

Note that we performed some data cleaning to include only conditions that we deemed to be complete and to make the metadata more usable.

In addition, well practice plotting with ggplot2 some more. If youre interested in more information about plotting with ggplot2, check out:

  • ggplot2 documentation
  • UC Business Analytics R Programming Guide An Introduction to ggplot2
  • r.statistics.co The Complete ggplot2 Tutorial - Part1
  • Harvard University Data Science Services R graphics with ggplot2 workshop notes

Setup

Well use the dplyr, ggplot2, and colorblindr libraries. First, well check if we need to install them.

Aside: why are we using devtools?

devtools is a package that is designed to:

make package development easier by providing R functions that simplify and expedite common tasks.

Here, we will use it for its package installation functionality. Specifically, we will use it to install packages from GitHub. This allows us to install packages that are not on CRAN or Bioconductor or to install development versions of packages that may have functionality that is not yet included in the most recent release.

Another handy function from devtools (that is imported from remotes) is install_version, which allows us to install a specific package version from CRAN. This can help with reproducibility.

# we need devtools to install colorblindr
if (!("devtools" %in% installed.packages())) {
  install.packages("devtools")
}

Other packages

# should have dplyr and ggplot2 from last notebook or earlier in the course, 
# but in the name of good practice...
if (!("dplyr" %in% installed.packages())) {
  install.packages("dplyr")
}

if (!("ggplot2" %in% installed.packages())) {

if (!("colorblindr" %in% installed.packages())) {

  install.packages("colorspace", repos = "http://R-Forge.R-project.org")

}

Read in data

Sample metadata

Read in the sample metadata, which is stored as a TSV file.

metadata_df <- read.delim(file.path("data", "GSE116436", 
                                    "metadata_GSE116436_cleaned.tsv"),
                          stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
head(metadata_df)

We can see we have sample identifiers and information about what cell line the samples came from and how they were treated.

Read in and explore the PLIER model

We saved the PLIER model as an RDS file, which allows us to save a single R object from our environment (e.g., when we trained the model ahead of time) and load it into a different session (now!). (Read more about the benefits of saving single objects in this post from Gavin Simpson.)

plier_results <- readRDS(file.path("models", "NCI60_PLIER_model.RDS"))

PLIER returns a large list with 14 elements. Well take a look at some of the elements.

The Z matrix contains the loadings for each latent variable.

dim(plier_results$Z)
[1] 5375  348

The B matrix contains the latent variable expression values for each sample.

dim(plier_results$B)
[1]  348 3977

The U matrix contains information about the relationships between the input pathway and the latent variables.

dim(plier_results$U)
[1] 628 348

The summary data.frame contains statistics about the relationships between input pathways and the latent variables.

head(plier_results$summary)

The latent variables from this model will be associated with a pathway if the gene expression data supports that there is some shared variation in the expression levels of genes in that pathway. It could be due to treatment with a drug or variation could arise from tissue- or cell line-specific differences.

Is there a latent variable associated with the proteasome pathway?

Well use the FDR column to filter out non-significant associations and the pathway column to find pathways associated with the term proteasome.

# filter is a dplyr function used to select *rows* that match certain 
# criteria
filter(plier_results$summary, FDR < 0.05,  # significant associations only
       # grepl returns TRUE when the pattern "proteasome" is found
       # in the pathway column
       grepl("proteasome", pathway, ignore.case = TRUE))

The LV index refers to the number of the latent variable that is significantly associated with this pathway. This corresponds to a row in the B matrix.

rownames(plier_results$B)[38]
[1] "38,KEGG_PROTEASOME"

We can look at the Z matrix to see what genes contribute most to this latent variable, like so:

head(sort(plier_results$Z[, 38], decreasing = TRUE), 10)
   PSMD1    PSMA4   PSMD14    PSMA5    PSMD3    PSMB2    PSMB1    PSMB3    PSMC4    PSMD2 
2.166147 2.096679 2.071370 1.938363 1.827945 1.773119 1.765783 1.756028 1.742245 1.618603

These genes are definitely all related to the proteasome!

We can make a data.frame that holds only the expression values for this latent variable.

proteasome_lv_df <- data.frame(geo_accession = colnames(plier_results$B),
                               proteasome_lv = plier_results$B[38, ])

We can use dplyr to join the LV38 expression values with the metadata to facilitate plotting.

proteasome_df <- inner_join(x = proteasome_lv_df,  # expression values
                            y = metadata_df,  # sample metadata
                            by = "geo_accession")  # use the sample id to join
Column `geo_accession` joining factor and character vector, coercing into character vector
head(proteasome_df)

Now the data.frame proteasome_df has the sample labels and the expression values for the proteasome-associated latent variables.

We can sort proteasome_df to get an idea of what samples have the highest expression values for this latent variable. Well use arrange from the dplyr library to do this. The inclusion of the desc function means it will be in descending order.

arrange(proteasome_df, desc(proteasome_lv))

All of the top values come from samples treated with bortezomib!

Line graph time!

We have time point information, so lets make a line graph to examine the expression values of proteasome-associated latent variable.

To simplify things, well look at only samples from lung. We can use filter from dplyr again to get a data.frame of samples that match these criteria.

lung_bortezomib_df <- filter(proteasome_df,
                             treatment == "bortezomib",
                             tissue == "Lung")

Lets make a plot of the data included in lung_bortezomib_df using ggplot2.

# this is the main way we pass data to ggplot2 and tell it what values to
# plot on which axis, etc.
ggplot(lung_bortezomib_df, 
       aes(x = time_hours,  # plot the time point on the x-axis
           y = proteasome_lv,  # plot the LV expression values on y-axis
           color = cell_line,  # color by individual cell line
           # we need to use group to make our line plot
           group = cell_line)) +  # the + operator allows us add layers
  geom_point() +  # we'll have points on our graph
  geom_line() +  # that are connected by a line
  facet_wrap(~ dose_nM) +  # use facets to separate dosages
  scale_color_OkabeIto()  # use this scale from colorblindr for accessibility

What do you think is happening in these samples?
